'''Wang Gen''' ({{zh|s=王艮|p=Wáng gěn}}), (born 20 July 1483 - died 2 January 1541) was a [[Ming dynasty]]  [[Neo-Confucianism|Neo-Confucian]] philosopher who popularized the teachings of [[Wang Yangming]].<ref name="Routledge, 2008 - The Routledge History of Chinese Philosophy - p 421">{{cite book|title=The Routledge History of Chinese Philosophy|editor=Bo Mou|publisher=[[Routledge]]|date=27 Oct 2008|pages=421|isbn=9781134249381|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UL1-AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA421&lpg=PA421&dq=%E7%8E%8B%E8%89%AE+%22Wang+Gen%22&source=bl&ots=jjYwZYi9PJ&sig=1kmKTEmC9OzZvg7t0Df8_Yd_XBk&hl=en&sa=X&ei=6LJkU6qXK4z_8QWdzIH4Dg&ved=0CGQQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=%E7%8E%8B%E8%89%AE%20%22Wang%20Gen%22&f=false|accessdate=3 May 2014}}</ref>  Wang was the founder of the [[:zh:泰州學派|Taizhou School]] ({{zh|t=泰州學派|s=泰州学派|p=Tàizhōu xuépài}}).<ref name="Routledge, 2008 - The Routledge History of Chinese Philosophy - p 421"/>

